oxidation reduction problems.

00:07:21.890 --> 00:07:24.510
And here are those rules, and
now let's see look at some

00:07:24.510 --> 00:07:35.110
examples of how we're going
to apply these rules.

00:07:35.110 --> 00:07:39.280
So, first let's look at a
compound that has lithium and

00:07:39.280 --> 00:07:47.450
oxygen in it.

00:07:47.450 --> 00:07:48.640
All right.

00:07:48.640 --> 00:07:53.930
What do I know about lithium's
oxidation number?

00:07:53.930 --> 00:07:55.950
What's it going to be?

00:07:55.950 --> 00:07:56.960
Plus 1.

00:07:56.960 --> 00:08:00.600
So, things in group 1 are
going to be plus 1,

00:08:00.600 --> 00:08:02.660
and I have 2 of them.

00:08:02.660 --> 00:08:04.600
So we're going to be using
one of those rules up

00:08:04.600 --> 00:08:06.120
there to assign it.

00:08:06.120 --> 00:08:07.300
What about oxygen?

00:08:07.300 --> 00:08:12.000
What's oxygen going to
be in this molecule?

00:08:12.000 --> 00:08:14.620
Minus 2.

00:08:14.620 --> 00:08:19.080
So it's not in a peroxide here,
so it'll be minus 2.

00:08:19.080 --> 00:08:24.290
And then we have plus 2 minus
2 is equal to 0, and that's

00:08:24.290 --> 00:08:27.540
good, because there's no charge
on this particular

00:08:27.540 --> 00:08:30.270
molecule, so all of the
oxidation numbers

00:08:30.270 --> 00:08:32.140
should add up to 0.

00:08:32.140 --> 00:08:33.630
That's also one of our rules.

00:08:33.630 --> 00:08:40.990
All right, so let's
look at p c l 5.

00:08:40.990 --> 00:08:47.010
So, what we know about oxidation
number of chloride?

00:08:47.010 --> 00:08:48.930
What are you guessing?

00:08:48.930 --> 00:08:50.710
Minus 1.

00:08:50.710 --> 00:08:55.130
What's the exception to that?

00:08:55.130 --> 00:08:59.680
When it's with what?

00:08:59.680 --> 00:09:02.100
When it's with oxygen
it can be different.

00:09:02.100 --> 00:09:04.470
All right, so there's
5 of those.

00:09:04.470 --> 00:09:07.670
I haven't told you anything
about phosphorous, but what

00:09:07.670 --> 00:09:09.470
can you guess it's
going to be?

00:09:09.470 --> 00:09:11.350
STUDENT: 5.

00:09:11.350 --> 00:09:14.100
PROFESSOR: I love that
enthusiasm, good.

00:09:14.100 --> 00:09:19.700
So, it will be 5, and so
overall, we're going

00:09:19.700 --> 00:09:22.800
to add up to 0.

00:09:22.800 --> 00:09:25.720
So you won't always have a rule
about everything in your

00:09:25.720 --> 00:09:29.020
