something that you can get a

00:09:29.020 --> 00:09:31.220
handle on and then predict
what the other

00:09:31.220 --> 00:09:34.660
thing is going to be.

00:09:34.660 --> 00:09:41.300
So let's do a couple more.

00:09:41.300 --> 00:09:47.030
So, what about h n o 3?

00:09:47.030 --> 00:09:51.030
So let's start with oxygen --
you told me about oxygen,

00:09:51.030 --> 00:09:52.660
what's oxygen going
to be here?

00:09:52.660 --> 00:09:55.320
STUDENT: Negative 2.

00:09:55.320 --> 00:09:57.590
PROFESSOR: Negative 2 and
there's 3 of those.

00:09:57.590 --> 00:10:01.600
And we need to have this
all add up to 0 again.

00:10:01.600 --> 00:10:03.280
So, what about hydrogen?

00:10:03.280 --> 00:10:05.990
STUDENT: Plus 1.

00:10:05.990 --> 00:10:07.330
PROFESSOR: Plus 1.

00:10:07.330 --> 00:10:09.170
What's the exception
to that rule?

00:10:09.170 --> 00:10:14.530
When its with a metal.

00:10:14.530 --> 00:10:19.260
So what does that leave
for nitrogen?

00:10:19.260 --> 00:10:21.400
Plus 5.

00:10:21.400 --> 00:10:23.920
And that will all add up.

00:10:23.920 --> 00:10:28.020
All right, so you're very good
at this, so let's bring in

00:10:28.020 --> 00:10:31.110
that clicker competition,
and you can tell

00:10:31.110 --> 00:10:56.560
me about this molecule.

00:10:56.560 --> 00:11:12.640
All right, 10 seconds.

00:11:12.640 --> 00:11:15.930
Excellent -- not necessarily for
the competition since most

00:11:15.930 --> 00:11:17.960
people got it right,
but I love seeing

00:11:17.960 --> 00:11:19.210
people get it right.

00:11:19.210 --> 00:11:31.150
So, 2 times plus 1 minus 2 is 0,
so we know our states here.

00:11:31.150 --> 00:11:33.390
And I'll just tell you another
thing you can do in doing

00:11:33.390 --> 00:11:36.330
these problems, if you recognize
that something is

00:11:36.330 --> 00:11:40.450
