00:12:08.650 --> 00:12:13.060
All right, so we looked
at some examples.

00:12:13.060 --> 00:12:16.640
So now we're going to give
some definitions.

00:12:16.640 --> 00:12:21.630
What is oxidation?

00:12:21.630 --> 00:12:23.300
What happens when something
is oxidized?

00:12:23.300 --> 00:12:24.010
Yup.

00:12:24.010 --> 00:12:34.700
So, when you oxidize something,
electrons are lost.

00:12:34.700 --> 00:12:37.270
What happens when you
reduce something?

00:12:37.270 --> 00:12:39.390
STUDENT: Gain electrons.

00:12:39.390 --> 00:12:41.370
PROFESSOR: You gain electrons.

00:12:41.370 --> 00:12:43.770
Most people are good with
those definitions.

00:12:43.770 --> 00:12:46.700
Here are some that give people
a little bit more trouble.

00:12:46.700 --> 00:12:49.200
Oxidizing agent.

00:12:49.200 --> 00:13:01.090
So it is an agent of oxidation,
so it accepts -- an

00:13:01.090 --> 00:13:03.980
oxidation agent is something
that wants to oxidize

00:13:03.980 --> 00:13:07.190
something else, so it
gets reduced itself.

00:13:07.190 --> 00:13:08.640
So it's an agent of oxidation.

00:13:08.640 --> 00:13:12.190
It runs around trying to oxidize
other things, but it

00:13:12.190 --> 00:13:15.190
itself is going to get reduced,
and then you can

00:13:15.190 --> 00:13:19.370
probably figure out what a
reducing agent is, it's an

00:13:19.370 --> 00:13:21.890
agent of reduction.

00:13:21.890 --> 00:13:24.520
And so it itself will
be oxidized.

00:13:24.520 --> 00:13:26.170
It'll try to reduce
something else.

00:13:26.170 --> 00:13:28.910
It'll run around trying to
reduce something, trying to

00:13:28.910 --> 00:13:33.600
give off its electrons, donate
its electrons so that it can

00:13:33.600 --> 00:13:36.780
be oxidized.

00:13:36.780 --> 00:13:39.840
So, keep these definitions in
mind, because you're going to

00:13:39.840 --> 00:13:47.580
be using them a lot
in this unit.

00:13:47.580 --> 00:13:49.580
So now we're going to use them,
we're going to look at a

00:13:49.580 --> 00:13:52.790
reaction, and we're going to
think about what's being

00:13:52.790 --> 00:13:57.340
oxidized and what is
being reduced.

00:13:57.340 --> 00:14:01.870
And this particular type of
reaction, a disproportionation

00:14:01.870 --> 00:14:10.760
reaction, the same element can
be both oxidized and reduced.

00:14:10.760 --> 00:14:14.890
So let's break this down
into two equations.

00:14:14.890 --> 00:14:17.660
In every reaction there's going
to be an oxidation and a

00:14:17.660 --> 00:14:20.820
reduction, and so you can
write those separately.

00:14:20.820 --> 00:14:23.940
And poor sodium, sodium is
getting kind of a jip.

00:14:23.940 --> 00:14:29.140
A lot in these last few units in
acid base, and here again,

00:14:29.140 --> 00:14:33.300
it's a spectator ion here, so
it doesn't even make it into

00:14:33.300 --> 00:14:34.670
the equation.

00:14:34.670 --> 00:14:38.430
And it was ineffective as a
conjugate acid, it hasn't

00:14:38.430 --> 00:14:40.160
really been doing very
much recently.

00:14:40.160 --> 00:14:41.290
But that's OK.

00:14:41.290 --> 00:14:44.620
All right, so let's look at
what's going on here and try

00:14:44.620 --> 00:14:47.540
to figure out what's happening
in terms of what's being

00:14:47.540 --> 00:14:50.490
reduced and what's
being oxidized.

00:14:50.490 --> 00:14:54.890
So let's start over here, let's
think about what the

00:14:54.890 --> 00:14:59.560
oxidation numbers are in this
particular molecule.

00:14:59.560 --> 00:15:05.130
So what would be true about
oxygen here and chloride.

00:15:05.130 --> 00:15:08.840
What do we know about this
combination of things in terms

00:15:08.840 --> 00:15:14.090
of oxidation numbers?

00:15:14.090 --> 00:15:25.990
So let's start with chloride,
what's that going to be here?

00:15:25.990 --> 00:15:28.410
So, we have a minus 2 here.

00:15:28.410 --> 00:15:32.010
And the whole thing is going to
be minus 1, and so what is

00:15:32.010 --> 00:15:32.450
that about chloride?

00:15:32.450 --> 00:15:35.900
Plus 1, right.

00:15:35.900 --> 00:15:37.950
So this is one of
the exceptions.

00:15:37.950 --> 00:15:41.650
Chloride is usually minus 1,
except when it's with oxygen,

00:15:41.650 --> 00:15:44.610
and here we have an overall
charge of the molecule of

00:15:44.610 --> 00:15:47.980
minus 1, so it all has to add
up to minus 1 and it does.

00:15:47.980 --> 00:15:51.190
All right, so now let's
do that side.

00:15:51.190 --> 00:15:54.030
So what's going on here?

00:15:54.030 --> 00:15:56.270
Are they going to be similar
or different?

00:15:56.270 --> 00:16:01.550
Let's start with the oxygen,
what's that going to be?

00:16:01.550 --> 00:16:04.190
So we have three negative 2's.

00:16:04.190 --> 00:16:07.360
It's not a peroxide, so it's
negative 2 for oxygen.

00:16:07.360 --> 00:16:11.300
The overall has to be
equal to minus 1, so

00:16:11.300 --> 00:16:12.380
what is chloride here?

00:16:12.380 --> 00:16:15.360
Plus 5, right.

00:16:15.360 --> 00:16:17.480
So that's unusual, but
that's what it is.

00:16:17.480 --> 00:16:19.780
So we use our rules.

00:16:19.780 --> 00:16:22.750
Chloride is usually minus 1,
except when it's with oxygen,

00:16:22.750 --> 00:16:24.780
and then it can be something
different.

00:16:24.780 --> 00:16:28.690
So, here chloride's going from
plus 1 to plus 5, so what's

00:16:28.690 --> 00:16:29.570
happening to it?

00:16:29.570 --> 00:16:37.740
Is it being oxidized
or reduced?

00:16:37.740 --> 00:16:38.210
Yup.

00:16:38.210 --> 00:16:41.450
So it's going from plus 1
to plus 5, so we have an

00:16:41.450 --> 00:16:43.200
oxidation going on.

00:16:43.200 --> 00:16:46.010
So to tell whether something
is an oxidation or not, you

00:16:46.010 --> 00:16:49.330
need to figure out what the
oxidation numbers are and then

00:16:49.330 --> 00:16:52.170
see what's changing in the
course of that reaction.

00:16:52.170 --> 00:16:57.800
All right, so down here, we've
already done this one, so we

00:16:57.800 --> 00:16:59.840
can put that down here.

00:16:59.840 --> 00:17:03.910
So we have minus 2 for oxygen,
overall minus 1, and so

00:17:03.910 --> 00:17:05.700
chloride is plus 1 again.

00:17:05.700 --> 00:17:08.090
And what's the oxidation
number on the

00:17:08.090 --> 00:17:11.010
other side for chlorine?

00:17:11.010 --> 00:17:12.310
Minus 1.

00:17:12.310 --> 00:17:15.300
I just have to look, and
so that's minus 1.

00:17:15.300 --> 00:17:20.680
So here we're going from plus 1
to minus 1, so what is that?

00:17:20.680 --> 00:17:22.320
That's a reduction.

00:17:22.320 --> 00:17:25.960
And if we had figured out that
they're both oxidations and

00:17:25.960 --> 00:17:28.280
something we would have done
incorrectly, because in these

00:17:28.280 --> 00:17:31.090
reactions you're going to have
oxidations and reductions.

00:17:31.090 --> 00:17:35.650
So, here, and this is
disproportionation.

00:17:35.650 --> 00:17:37.280
So, you have chloride in one
state, and in another, it's

00:17:37.280 --> 00:17:43.030
undergoing a reduction.

00:17:43.030 --> 00:17:46.820
OK, so that's how you sort of
think about what's happening

00:17:46.820 --> 00:17:48.720
in these types of reactions.

00:17:48.720 --> 00:17:51.440
So now we need to balance
reactions.

00:17:51.440 --> 00:17:54.220
And this is very important in
getting the correct answer to

00:17:54.220 --> 00:17:58.430
the later problems, and so we'll
go through an example of

00:17:58.430 --> 00:17:59.670
how you're going to balance.

00:17:59.670 --> 00:18:01.740
You need to think about
whether it's an acidic

00:18:01.740 --> 00:18:03.670
solution or basic solution,
and we'll talk

00:18:03.670 --> 00:18:07.020
about that at the end.

00:18:07.020 --> 00:18:11.820
So, first here, we can look at
the two 1/2 reactions going

00:18:11.820 --> 00:18:14.410
on, we have iron, we have
chromium, and so we're going

00:18:14.410 --> 00:18:17.590
to look at those separately.

00:18:17.590 --> 00:18:22.190
So here is the first one, and
let's think about what's

00:18:22.190 --> 00:18:23.870
happening over here.

00:18:23.870 --> 00:18:38.010
So, what would our oxidation
number of the oxygen be here?

00:18:38.010 --> 00:18:39.590
What is happening to it?

00:18:39.590 --> 00:18:42.800
So, figure out what the
oxidation numbers are of the

00:18:42.800 --> 00:18:45.480
chromium on one side, you know
what it is on the other side,

00:18:45.480 --> 00:19:06.270
and then tell me what's
happening to it.

