2 to iron plus 3.

00:20:26.610 --> 00:20:29.400
Just yell it out, what is that?

00:20:29.400 --> 00:20:30.970
Yeah.

00:20:30.970 --> 00:20:33.500
So here we have our oxidation.

00:20:33.500 --> 00:20:35.500
Now let's balance this.

00:20:35.500 --> 00:20:39.180
And I left some nice blanks in
your notes, but not so many

00:20:39.180 --> 00:20:42.640
that you won't be able to keep
up and you should feel free to

00:20:42.640 --> 00:20:46.420
yell out the answers and we'll
go through balancing this

00:20:46.420 --> 00:20:49.430
pretty quickly.

00:20:49.430 --> 00:20:51.310
So there's a couple of
different rules.

00:20:51.310 --> 00:20:53.860
I'll just say some books have
things differently.

00:20:53.860 --> 00:20:56.330
If you can get the right answer,
you can use whatever

00:20:56.330 --> 00:20:58.070
procedure you want.

00:20:58.070 --> 00:21:01.870
I have found in the past that
this particular procedure a

00:21:01.870 --> 00:21:06.150
lot of people find to be the
easiest. So I'll teach you

00:21:06.150 --> 00:21:08.880
this one, but you're free
to use whichever ones

00:21:08.880 --> 00:21:09.830
work well for you.

00:21:09.830 --> 00:21:13.270
All right, so the first thing
we want to do is balance all

00:21:13.270 --> 00:21:17.060
elements that are not
oxygen or hydrogen.

00:21:17.060 --> 00:21:19.030
To make it equal on both sides,
we're going to do

00:21:19.030 --> 00:21:21.020
oxygen and hydrogen later.

00:21:21.020 --> 00:21:25.590
But what do we need to do
up here to balance our

00:21:25.590 --> 00:21:29.440
non-oxygens?

00:21:29.440 --> 00:21:31.470
We need to add a what?

00:21:31.470 --> 00:21:35.150
A 2.

00:21:35.150 --> 00:21:38.250
So we need to add a 2 over here,
two chromiums here, two

00:21:38.250 --> 00:21:39.390
on the other side.

00:21:39.390 --> 00:21:40.590
What about for iron?

00:21:40.590 --> 00:21:43.230
Nothing.

00:21:43.230 --> 00:21:46.560
All right, so that was
pretty simple.

00:21:46.560 --> 00:21:52.530
Now, in this procedure you add
water to balance the oxygens.

00:21:52.530 --> 00:21:56.400
So, what are we going
to do up here.

00:21:56.400 --> 00:22:01.560
How many waters do
we need to add?

00:22:01.560 --> 00:22:05.270
So we need to add 7 waters.

00:22:05.270 --> 00:22:08.200
And the bottom one, bottom one's
pretty easy so far, we

00:22:08.200 --> 00:22:11.220
don't have to do anything.

00:22:11.220 --> 00:22:15.380
So, go ahead and write
in your 7 waters.

00:22:15.380 --> 00:22:18.710
Next step is we're going to
balance the hydrogens that we

00:22:18.710 --> 00:22:24.780
just added, and we can balance
here with h plus, and I say

00:22:24.780 --> 00:22:26.850
here's one place that
books are different.

00:22:26.850 --> 00:22:29.400
Some of them balance in the
more sort of technically

00:22:29.400 --> 00:22:32.310
correct way with hydroium ions,
but then your oxygens

00:22:32.310 --> 00:22:36.340
get unbalanced again, so it's
OK to use the simpler

00:22:36.340 --> 00:22:39.520
approach, and just balance
with h plus.

00:22:39.520 --> 00:22:42.380
So how many h plusses
do we need to add to

00:22:42.380 --> 00:22:46.720
balance the top part?

00:22:46.720 --> 00:22:49.840
Yup, so we need to
add 14 over here.

00:22:49.840 --> 00:22:53.550
Again, the bottom one,
nothing to do.

00:22:53.550 --> 00:22:56.800
Pretty simple.

00:22:56.800 --> 00:23:00.280
Now we need to balance the
charge, so we just added h

00:23:00.280 --> 00:23:04.770
plusses, so we just added some
charge to this, and now we

00:23:04.770 --> 00:23:07.720
have to balance the overall
charge, so you want the charge

00:23:07.720 --> 00:23:11.350
on one side of the equation to
be equal to the charge on the

00:23:11.350 --> 00:23:13.440
other side of the equation.

00:23:13.440 --> 00:23:17.150
So how many electrons are we
going to have to add to this

00:23:17.150 --> 00:23:30.860
top equation to balance
the charge?

00:23:30.860 --> 00:23:31.700
I heard the answer.

00:23:31.700 --> 00:23:34.740
6.

00:23:34.740 --> 00:23:36.410
So we have to add 6.

00:23:36.410 --> 00:23:41.530
I told you, this unit involves
adding and subtracting in your

00:23:41.530 --> 00:23:45.430
head, and you always want to
check your work when you're

00:23:45.430 --> 00:23:49.340
doing this on an exam, because
it's really sad when you lose

00:23:49.340 --> 00:23:52.220
points for something that is
adding and subtracting.

00:23:52.220 --> 00:23:55.640
So you want to make sure that
you don't lose points on these

00:23:55.640 --> 00:23:57.560
on an exam.

00:23:57.560 --> 00:24:00.120
So what about the bottom --
finally we get to do something

00:24:00.120 --> 00:24:03.550
with the bottom one,
what do we do?

00:24:03.550 --> 00:24:07.010
So, we add how many electrons?

00:24:07.010 --> 00:24:08.750
1, right.

00:24:08.750 --> 00:24:12.530
OK, so now our charge
is balanced.

00:24:12.530 --> 00:24:18.350
So now, we want to multiply up
one of the 1/2 reactions so

00:24:18.350 --> 00:24:23.190
that the electrons are going to
cancel, and so what do we

00:24:23.190 --> 00:24:27.950
have to multiply by the bottom
equation so that the electrons

00:24:27.950 --> 00:24:30.320
cancel with the first?

00:24:30.320 --> 00:24:32.440
6.

00:24:32.440 --> 00:24:40.180
So we have 6, 6, and 6.

00:24:40.180 --> 00:24:43.520
And now, we're going to add
those together and make the

00:24:43.520 --> 00:24:48.750
appropriate cancellations.

00:24:48.750 --> 00:24:52.120
So here is our overall equation
-- we have the 6

00:24:52.120 --> 00:24:56.690
electrons, the 14 protons, we
have our chromium oxide

00:24:56.690 --> 00:25:00.970
compound, we have the 6 iron 2
plusses, on the other side,

00:25:00.970 --> 00:25:05.060
the 2 chromium 3 plusses, the
7 waters, the 6 iron 3

00:25:05.060 --> 00:25:07.150
plusses, and the 6 electrons.

00:25:07.150 --> 00:25:11.010
So, we should be able to cancel
the electrons, so we

00:25:11.010 --> 00:25:15.630
cancel those out.

00:25:15.630 --> 00:25:17.420
And now we want to double
check that,

00:25:17.420 --> 00:25:18.710
in fact, it's balanced.

00:25:18.710 --> 00:25:21.300
Again, this is very important to
do on the test, it's really

00:25:21.300 --> 00:25:24.230
easy to make some kind of math
mistake, but you should be

00:25:24.230 --> 00:25:26.190
able to figure it out
at this point.

00:25:26.190 --> 00:25:29.000
It won't be balanced if you've
made a math mistake.

00:25:29.000 --> 00:25:32.830
So there should be 14 hydrogens
over here, 14 over

00:25:32.830 --> 00:25:36.670
there, 2 chromiums, 2 chromiums,
you have 7 oxygens

00:25:36.670 --> 00:25:40.590
here, 7 oxygens there,
6 irons, 6 irons.

00:25:40.590 --> 00:25:44.680
And the charge also should be
balanced on both sides.

00:25:44.680 --> 00:25:47.290
So you can double check
that and if it's

00:25:47.290 --> 00:25:48.910
good, then you're done.

00:25:48.910 --> 00:25:52.970
And this was in acidic solution,
so we should have

00:25:52.970 --> 00:25:57.240
again this number and a charge
of plus 24 on each side,

00:25:57.240 --> 00:26:01.830
double check, make sure
it's correct.

00:26:01.830 --> 00:26:05.580
So, that was acidic solution
and we ended up with an

00:26:05.580 --> 00:26:07.660
equation that had
h plusses in it.

00:26:07.660 --> 00:26:11.740
You can also be asked to do it
in basic solution, and again,

00:26:11.740 --> 00:26:14.960
books have different
approaches here.

00:26:14.960 --> 00:26:19.200
What I like to do is the
simplest thing, which is to

00:26:19.200 --> 00:26:23.480
use the same steps all the way
up to here to get your same

00:26:23.480 --> 00:26:27.380
answer that you had for the
acidic solution, and then

00:26:27.380 --> 00:26:29.590
neutralize it at this point.

00:26:29.590 --> 00:26:33.955
So, adjust the p h in quotes
by adding hydroxide ions to

00:26:33.955 --> 00:26:40.090
both sides, and so, if we have
14 h plusses here, we can add

00:26:40.090 --> 00:26:45.120
14 o h's on one side, and 14 o
h minus on the other side.

00:26:45.120 --> 00:26:49.760
And then we can add those
guys together.

00:26:49.760 --> 00:26:52.670
So we have now 14 waters
over here.

00:26:52.670 --> 00:26:56.310
And we have still our 7 waters
on this side, and then the 14

00:26:56.310 --> 00:26:58.570
hydroxides on this side.

00:26:58.570 --> 00:27:00.710
And now, we should be
able to cancel out

00:27:00.710 --> 00:27:03.810
some of those waters.

00:27:03.810 --> 00:27:08.090
So, we had 14 over here, 7 over
here, so we can just have

00:27:08.090 --> 00:27:09.530
7 on this side.

00:27:09.530 --> 00:27:11.480
And now we have an equation
that looks like

00:27:11.480 --> 00:27:13.040
it's in basic solution.

00:27:13.040 --> 00:27:16.090
So instead of having h plus,
which you would have in acid,

00:27:16.090 --> 00:27:18.990
you have hydroxide for
basic solution.

00:27:18.990 --> 00:27:20.340
So you can follow
the same rules.

00:27:20.340 --> 00:27:21.760
Again, some books do
it differently.

00:27:21.760 --> 00:27:25.030
I think this is the simplest way
to do it, the least likely

00:27:25.030 --> 00:27:29.510
to make those kind of adding
and subtracting errors.

00:27:29.510 --> 00:27:31.480
So those are sort of the
fundamentals you

00:27:31.480 --> 00:27:32.720
need for this unit.

00:27:32.720 --> 00:27:36.120
You need to figure out oxidation
numbers, looking at

00:27:36.120 --> 00:27:40.120
the composition of a molecule,
and you need to be able to

00:27:40.120 --> 00:27:41.390
balance equations.

00:27:41.390 --> 00:27:44.370
When you can do that, you can
go on to do other things.

00:27:44.370 --> 00:27:49.350
So, at this point -- oh, let me
