00:33:09.520 --> 00:33:13.570
then we have a wire across where
we can measure voltage.

00:33:13.570 --> 00:33:17.000
So, let's think about what is
happening on each side.

00:33:17.000 --> 00:33:22.260
So in one beaker you're going
to have an oxidation

00:33:22.260 --> 00:33:24.570
reduction, and in the
other beaker you're

00:33:24.570 --> 00:33:26.980
going to have a reduction.

00:33:26.980 --> 00:33:30.050
So if we think about what's
happening over here, you could

00:33:30.050 --> 00:33:33.750
have a zinc system, is
oxidized from zinc 0

00:33:33.750 --> 00:33:36.190
to zinc plus 2.

00:33:36.190 --> 00:33:39.270
And so, this is sort of a view
of what would be happening at

00:33:39.270 --> 00:33:42.720
the electrode, you have zinc
solid or zinc 0, and you've

00:33:42.720 --> 00:33:45.360
also have zinc plus
2 in solution.

00:33:45.360 --> 00:33:50.690
And so, as you take a zinc solid
atom, going into zinc

00:33:50.690 --> 00:33:53.550
plus 2, you can have an
oxidation reaction.

00:33:53.550 --> 00:33:56.590
And here would be the
equation going down.

00:33:56.590 --> 00:33:59.650
So zinc solid to zinc plus
2 with two electrons.

00:33:59.650 --> 00:34:03.370
Those electrons can go through
to our other beaker on this

00:34:03.370 --> 00:34:09.770
other side, and so here we have
a copper solid electrode

00:34:09.770 --> 00:34:15.150
or a cathode in this case, and
we have copper plus 2 in

00:34:15.150 --> 00:34:18.940
solution, which is being reduced
to copper solid, and

00:34:18.940 --> 00:34:22.220
so we're plating on to our
electrode on this side.

00:34:22.220 --> 00:34:25.040
And so, here we have the
reduction reaction, copper 2

00:34:25.040 --> 00:34:27.570
with two electrons going
to copper solid.

00:34:27.570 --> 00:34:29.630
So our oxidation is
happening at an

00:34:29.630 --> 00:34:31.280
electrode called the anode.

00:34:31.280 --> 00:34:33.030
The reduction is
happening in an

00:34:33.030 --> 00:34:34.480
electrode called the cathode.

00:34:34.480 --> 00:34:38.260
And as these reactions occur,
you're changing the charge on

00:34:38.260 --> 00:34:39.380
either side.

00:34:39.380 --> 00:34:43.030
So, you have this salt bridge,
and so to neutralize the

00:34:43.030 --> 00:34:46.850
change in charge, you would have
negative ions come down

00:34:46.850 --> 00:34:49.120
here, because we're producing
more plus 2.

00:34:49.120 --> 00:34:52.790
And on the other side potassium
is going in as we're

00:34:52.790 --> 00:34:56.470
going from copper plus 2 to
copper solid, again, to

00:34:56.470 --> 00:34:59.430
balance this change in charge
that's occurring.

00:34:59.430 --> 00:35:03.800
So those are the basic
components of a simple

00:35:03.800 --> 00:35:06.980
electrochemical cell.

00:35:06.980 --> 00:35:09.510
So, we could talk about the
cell -- here's some

00:35:09.510 --> 00:35:12.820
nomenclature that represents
the cell.

00:35:12.820 --> 00:35:18.120
So, the one that I just showed
you, you have one electrode, a

00:35:18.120 --> 00:35:23.670
zinc solid, and we also have
zinc plus 2 in solution.

00:35:23.670 --> 00:35:27.650
You have a single line between
the solid and the zinc plus 2

00:35:27.650 --> 00:35:30.640
ions in solution, that indicates
there's a phase

00:35:30.640 --> 00:35:34.610
boundary, so you're changing
phase from solid to aqueous.

00:35:34.610 --> 00:35:38.600
Then if you see two little lines
that tells you, okay,

00:35:38.600 --> 00:35:41.450
one part of the reaction's in
one beaker, the other part is

00:35:41.450 --> 00:35:44.240
in the other beaker, that
represents the salt bridge

00:35:44.240 --> 00:35:47.580
which separates out the
two 1/2 reactions.

00:35:47.580 --> 00:35:50.360
And then on this side, we're
going from copper 2 in

00:35:50.360 --> 00:35:54.130
solution, single line which
indicates the phase boundary,

00:35:54.130 --> 00:35:59.210
to a copper solid over here.

00:35:59.210 --> 00:36:08.150
So the amount of charge that
goes through the system, it

00:36:08.150 --> 00:36:12.850
depends -- and how much of the
zinc that is consumed or the

00:36:12.850 --> 00:36:15.960
copper that is deposited, is
proportional to that charge,

00:36:15.960 --> 00:36:18.750
the number of electrons that
go through the system, and

00:36:18.750 --> 00:36:23.160
this is called Faraday's law.

00:36:23.160 --> 00:36:26.280
So let's look at what is
happening a little bit here,

00:36:26.280 --> 00:36:30.760
so we have a little movie that
shows the oxidation reaction.

00:36:30.760 --> 00:36:35.800
So in green is the electrode,
and then here are the water

00:36:35.800 --> 00:36:38.790
molecules, and let's look
at what happens when

00:36:38.790 --> 00:36:40.660
there's this oxidation.

00:36:40.660 --> 00:36:42.610
So here things are floating
around, and

00:36:42.610 --> 00:36:43.740
there go the electrons.

00:36:43.740 --> 00:36:47.860
And this pops off into
solutions, so if this is zinc,

00:36:47.860 --> 00:36:50.970
so then as this is happening,
we have a zinc plus 2 now,

00:36:50.970 --> 00:36:51.990
it's aqueous.

00:36:51.990 --> 00:36:54.310
There go electrons, we
have our oxidation.

00:36:54.310 --> 00:36:57.320
Here comes off zinc plus 2
floating around, there's

00:36:57.320 --> 00:37:00.280
another zinc plus 2 that
just came off.

00:37:00.280 --> 00:37:04.600
And so our electrode here is
being consumed as this

00:37:04.600 --> 00:37:06.290
oxidation occurs.

00:37:06.290 --> 00:37:09.430
I think it's really cool, the
electrons, you can see them as

00:37:09.430 --> 00:37:13.790
this green going along
in this movie.

00:37:13.790 --> 00:37:18.250
So, this is a little thing to
think about what's happening.

00:37:18.250 --> 00:37:21.520
So what's happening at the
cathode, we have a reduction.

00:37:21.520 --> 00:37:24.230
So if we have our copper
ions are going to

00:37:24.230 --> 00:37:25.990
plate onto our electrode.

00:37:25.990 --> 00:37:28.890
So here in blue is the
electrode, and again the water

00:37:28.890 --> 00:37:32.530
molecules, here's a little
copper 2 in solution.

00:37:32.530 --> 00:37:37.010
And when it gets electrons and
gets reduced, it's going to

00:37:37.010 --> 00:37:40.450
start plating, so let's
take a look at that.

00:37:40.450 --> 00:37:42.990
So, here's -- oh, there
comes the electrons.

00:37:42.990 --> 00:37:45.770
And so now it becomes part of
the electrode there, the

00:37:45.770 --> 00:37:49.160
electrons come in, and so you're
building up, you're

00:37:49.160 --> 00:37:51.970
adding, your plating on
to your electrode.

00:37:51.970 --> 00:37:55.380
Now it got its electrons, it
got reduced, got reduced

00:37:55.380 --> 00:38:05.160
again, and it becomes solid, and
plates onto the electrode.

00:38:05.160 --> 00:38:08.380
And we see the electrons
coming in.

00:38:08.380 --> 00:38:11.620
So again, the amount of current
that flows, the number

00:38:11.620 --> 00:38:14.860
of electrons that flow are going
to be proportional to

00:38:14.860 --> 00:38:18.600
the chemistry that's happening
at the two electrodes.

00:38:18.600 --> 00:38:22.540
So you can figure out how much
zinc would be consumed, how

00:38:22.540 --> 00:38:25.440
much of the zinc solid electrode
could be consumed,

00:38:25.440 --> 00:38:28.600
and how much copper would be
deposited on the copper

00:38:28.600 --> 00:38:32.380
electrode for a particular
amount of current.

00:38:32.380 --> 00:38:36.910
So say we have 1 amp of current
for 1 hour, what are

00:38:36.910 --> 00:38:39.600
we going to do to our system?

00:38:39.600 --> 00:38:44.100
So we can calculate this out,
so we use this equation to

00:38:44.100 --> 00:38:46.420
find out how much charge is
going to pass through the

00:38:46.420 --> 00:38:50.500
system, we have this term q,
the magnitude of charge and

00:38:50.500 --> 00:38:54.170
it's in Coulombs, those are our
units, and that's equal to

00:38:54.170 --> 00:39:00.310
the current in amps, and just
for unit conversion, amps are

00:39:00.310 --> 00:39:02.910
Coulombs per second, so that's
very convenient because we're

00:39:02.910 --> 00:39:07.510
going to take the current and
times second, so times time.

00:39:07.510 --> 00:39:12.520
And so if we work that out, we
had 1 amp and we had 1 hour,

00:39:12.520 --> 00:39:18.660
so we're going to have 3,600
Coulombs that are our

00:39:18.660 --> 00:39:21.110
magnitude of our charge.

00:39:21.110 --> 00:39:25.570
So once we know that, we can
convert, using Faraday's

00:39:25.570 --> 00:39:29.720
constant from charge into moles
of electrons that had to

00:39:29.720 --> 00:39:33.870
pass through the system to
generate that kind of current.

00:39:33.870 --> 00:39:37.370
And here is our friend Faraday's
constant, and so

00:39:37.370 --> 00:39:39.680
that's in Coulombs per mole.

00:39:39.680 --> 00:39:43.570
And so, we can we can convert
the number of Coulombs into

00:39:43.570 --> 00:39:46.970
the number of moles of electrons
that were passed

00:39:46.970 --> 00:39:48.540
through the system with
that amount of

00:39:48.540 --> 00:39:51.860
current, 1 amp for 1 hour.

00:39:51.860 --> 00:39:56.080
Now, how is this going to relate
to the zinc consumed or

00:39:56.080 --> 00:39:57.920
the copper deposited?

00:39:57.920 --> 00:40:00.430
So we know the total number
of moles that

00:40:00.430 --> 00:40:02.660
passed through the system.

00:40:02.660 --> 00:40:06.810
And so, then we have to think
about for every 1 mole of zinc

00:40:06.810 --> 00:40:12.020
that was consumed, how many
moles of electrons went

00:40:12.020 --> 00:40:13.590
through the system?

00:40:13.590 --> 00:40:17.560
So why don't you yell
out and tell me what

00:40:17.560 --> 00:40:18.600
you think that is.

00:40:18.600 --> 00:40:20.900
What do you think?

00:40:20.900 --> 00:40:26.410
2, right.

00:40:26.410 --> 00:40:30.360
So we are going from zinc
solid to zinc plus 2.

00:40:30.360 --> 00:40:33.130
So, we need to do -- to consume

00:40:33.130 --> 00:40:35.590
one, we need two electrons.

00:40:35.590 --> 00:40:42.410
So then we can look up the
atomic weight of zinc and

00:40:42.410 --> 00:40:45.470
calculate the number of grams.

00:40:45.470 --> 00:40:49.160
We can do the same
with copper.

00:40:49.160 --> 00:40:52.440
So for one mole of copper
deposited, how many moles of

00:40:52.440 --> 00:40:56.800
electrons needed to pass
through the system?

00:40:56.800 --> 00:41:02.480
two, right.

00:41:02.480 --> 00:41:06.630
And then we look up the atomic
weight, which is very similar,

00:41:06.630 --> 00:41:09.820
and actually with significant
figures, it's the same amount,

00:41:09.820 --> 00:41:13.180
which won't be true
for most things.

00:41:13.180 --> 00:41:19.020
All right, so these problems
are not too complicated.

00:41:19.020 --> 00:41:21.470
So let me just tell you a little
bit more about types of

00:41:21.470 --> 00:41:24.670
electrodes that can be used.

00:41:24.670 --> 00:41:27.900
It's not always true that you
have to use electrodes that

00:41:27.900 --> 00:41:31.210
are going to be consumed
or have species

00:41:31.210 --> 00:41:32.700
deposited on them.

00:41:32.700 --> 00:41:36.370
You can use an inert electrode,
such as a platinum

00:41:36.370 --> 00:41:39.640
electorate, and here is
an example of that.

00:41:39.640 --> 00:41:44.750
So here, this cell has a
platinum electrode, and the

00:41:44.750 --> 00:41:47.180
reaction that's happening, you
have actually two things in

00:41:47.180 --> 00:41:50.510
solution instead of going from
a solid to a solution.

00:41:50.510 --> 00:41:54.470
So this is just another example
of a type of cell.

00:41:54.470 --> 00:41:57.580
So let's think about, then, what
equations we would write

00:41:57.580 --> 00:42:00.180
for this chemistry and
what's going on.

00:42:00.180 --> 00:42:03.810
So over here at the cathode,
what happens at a cathode,

00:42:03.810 --> 00:42:11.430
oxidation or reduction?

00:42:11.430 --> 00:42:13.040
I'm hearing somewhat
of a consensus.

00:42:13.040 --> 00:42:13.850
That's correct.

00:42:13.850 --> 00:42:14.240
Reduction.

00:42:14.240 --> 00:42:17.950
That's the thing you're going to
need to memorize, it'll be

00:42:17.950 --> 00:42:20.390
important in doing problems
later on.

00:42:20.390 --> 00:42:23.720
So, what is the reduction
reaction that you imagine

00:42:23.720 --> 00:42:26.000
would be happening if
you have copper plus

00:42:26.000 --> 00:42:31.590
2 and copper solid?

00:42:31.590 --> 00:42:34.940
So, if you're reducing it,
you're going to be reducing

00:42:34.940 --> 00:42:38.400
copper plus 2 with two electrons
to copper solid.

00:42:38.400 --> 00:42:41.280
So, same reaction
we saw before.

00:42:41.280 --> 00:42:42.930
So what about over here.

00:42:42.930 --> 00:42:46.940
This is the anode, which has the
oxidation reaction going

00:42:46.940 --> 00:42:50.130
on, and what oxidation reaction
can you imagine

00:42:50.130 --> 00:42:53.660
happening with chromium plus
3 and chromium plus 2.

00:42:53.660 --> 00:43:03.760
What's going to what?

00:43:03.760 --> 00:43:06.350
So, you're going from plus
2 to plus 3 with

00:43:06.350 --> 00:43:08.370
one electron here.

00:43:08.370 --> 00:43:11.440
So that would be the
oxidation reaction.

00:43:11.440 --> 00:43:13.490
So let's think about how
we would actually

00:43:13.490 --> 00:43:15.200
write this down then.

00:43:15.200 --> 00:43:18.530
So the notation for this type of
cell, we're going to have a

00:43:18.530 --> 00:43:22.260
platinum that indicates the
electrode, a single line that

00:43:22.260 --> 00:43:23.940
indicates a phase boundary.

00:43:23.940 --> 00:43:27.550
And in solution, you have the
chromium plus 2, chromium plus

00:43:27.550 --> 00:43:29.320
3, those are both aqueous,
so they have a

00:43:29.320 --> 00:43:30.840
comma between them.

00:43:30.840 --> 00:43:34.950
So this is on one side in one of
the beakers, so that's the

00:43:34.950 --> 00:43:37.100
reaction at the anode.

00:43:37.100 --> 00:43:40.910
And then we have a bar here that
indicates a salt bridge.

00:43:40.910 --> 00:43:44.390
And then in the other beaker, we
would have the copper plus

00:43:44.390 --> 00:43:47.500
2 and the copper solid,
separated by a single line,

00:43:47.500 --> 00:43:49.370
because there's a phase boundary
between the aqueous

00:43:49.370 --> 00:43:50.890
and the solid.

00:43:50.890 --> 00:43:54.360
And then here are our
two equations.

00:43:54.360 --> 00:43:57.840
At the anode, we have
copper plus 2.

00:43:57.840 --> 00:44:00.580
Aqueous going to copper
plus 3 aqueous in an

00:44:00.580 --> 00:44:02.370
electron at the cathode.

00:44:02.370 --> 00:44:05.120
We have copper plus 2 aqueous
and two electrons going to

00:44:05.120 --> 00:44:06.310
copper solid.

00:44:06.310 --> 00:44:08.950
So those are our two equations
and how we

00:44:08.950 --> 00:44:12.680
would write that down.

00:44:12.680 --> 00:44:14.760
Another example of an electrode

00:44:14.760 --> 00:44:16.700
is a hydrogen electrode.

00:44:16.700 --> 00:44:18.070
And this is very common.

00:44:18.070 --> 00:44:21.900
In fact, most potential standard
reduction potentials,

00:44:21.900 --> 00:44:25.400
or as they're also known,
oxidation reduction potentials

00:44:25.400 --> 00:44:29.100
are measured against a standard
hydrogen electrode,

00:44:29.100 --> 00:44:31.970
and it'll be abbreviated
s h e.

00:44:31.970 --> 00:44:34.985
And so, if you see it was
measured against s h e, you

00:44:34.985 --> 00:44:36.870
will now know what that means.

00:44:36.870 --> 00:44:39.510
So that's a standard
hydrogen electrode.

00:44:39.510 --> 00:44:41.790
So there's a couple of
different variations.

00:44:41.790 --> 00:44:45.200
It can be used at the cathode
or at the anode.

00:44:45.200 --> 00:44:50.280
And so, if you're using it
at the cathode, h plus is

00:44:50.280 --> 00:44:54.100
reduced, and at the anode,
h 2 is oxidized.

00:44:54.100 --> 00:44:58.750
And often you have a platinum
system there as well, for the

00:44:58.750 --> 00:45:02.260
standard hydrogen, so platinum
is commonly used in a standard

00:45:02.260 --> 00:45:04.000
hydrogen electrode.

00:45:04.000 --> 00:45:08.350
So, let's just sort of look at
a little picture of this.

00:45:08.350 --> 00:45:11.975
So here, we may have like a
glass cylinder here, we're

00:45:11.975 --> 00:45:13.680
pumping in h 2 gas.

00:45:13.680 --> 00:45:16.740
And here you can see it
sort of bubbling down.

00:45:16.740 --> 00:45:20.050
We may have a solution of
hydrochloric acid, which would

00:45:20.050 --> 00:45:22.750
have a lot of h plus in it,
and so this would be a

00:45:22.750 --> 00:45:27.000
hydrogen electrode on one side,
the other side may have

00:45:27.000 --> 00:45:30.070
something more common or
something that we saw before

00:45:30.070 --> 00:45:33.290
with the zinc solid and
the zinc in solution.

00:45:33.290 --> 00:45:37.670
So since on this side we have
the cathode, of we can write

00:45:37.670 --> 00:45:42.670
about the h plus aqueous, a bar
for the phase transition

00:45:42.670 --> 00:45:47.300
to h 2 gas, and then we indicate
that there's also a

00:45:47.300 --> 00:45:49.940
platinum electrode
going on here.

00:45:49.940 --> 00:45:53.230
And the other side is what we
saw before, the zinc solid and

00:45:53.230 --> 00:45:54.550
the zinc plus 2.

00:45:54.550 --> 00:45:56.920
So you're just introducing
different types of electrodes

00:45:56.920 --> 00:46:00.360
that you may be seeing in
this particular unit.

00:46:00.360 --> 00:46:02.550
And again, you want to remember
what reaction's going

00:46:02.550 --> 00:46:04.590
on at the cathode,
and at the anode.

00:46:04.590 --> 00:46:14.070
All right, so just very briefly,
I will mention cell

00:46:14.070 --> 00:46:16.490
potential, which has many
different names -- cell

00:46:16.490 --> 00:46:19.880
voltage, EMF it's
often called.

00:46:19.880 --> 00:46:23.020
And so the flow of electrons
generates a potential

00:46:23.020 --> 00:46:26.900
difference between the
electrodes in the current.

00:46:26.900 --> 00:46:34.320
And this can be related back
to our friend, delta g.

00:46:34.320 --> 00:46:39.650
So in this equation you have
this potential difference

00:46:39.650 --> 00:46:44.760
that's generated by the flow
of the electrons, and that

00:46:44.760 --> 00:46:49.960
times Faraday's constant times
the number moles of electrons,

00:46:49.960 --> 00:46:52.590
and if you have a negative sign
here, that's equal to the

00:46:52.590 --> 00:46:56.040
free energy of the cell.

00:46:56.040 --> 00:47:00.850
So we can relate that back.

00:47:00.850 --> 00:47:03.340
And a little bit
of information.

00:47:03.340 --> 00:47:05.390
We have the standard
terms as well.

00:47:05.390 --> 00:47:09.010
We can have the delta e nought,
the cell potential,

00:47:09.010 --> 00:47:11.810
cell voltage, you'll see
many names for this.

00:47:11.810 --> 00:47:14.410
And that's when the products
and reactants are in their

00:47:14.410 --> 00:47:15.860
standard states.

00:47:15.860 --> 00:47:18.740
The units we're talking about
here are in volts, sometimes

00:47:18.740 --> 00:47:22.690
you'll see things reported
in millivolts as well.

